) is the minimal statistic needed for Chapter 1’s objects to propagate consistently into later geometry, entropy, and thermo-fusion chapters.



What Changed in the Equations
The foundational valence equation was transformed from a single, scalar quantity into a two-channel system that preserves relational information.

Symmetric Channel: The core valence equation was updated to include a coherence coefficient (ρ 
12
​
 ) and a new Coherence Floor (CF). The CF, a small, Gaussian-like term, was added to ensure the model remains stable and auditable even when glyphs are nearly orthogonal (ρ 
12
​
 ≈0).

Antisymmetric Channel (Ω): A new, separate channel was added to capture directionality and non-commutativity. This elegant solution ensures that order-sensitive effects, like directed drift, are measured without corrupting the symmetric energy term.

How We Validated It
We moved from conceptual debates to a rigorous, auditable protocol. This involved:

Targeted Datasets: We focused our validation on the two regimes that caused our previous model to fail: near-zero coherence and anti-aligned coherence.

Precise Tolerances: We set statistically derived pass/fail tolerances, ensuring that our results were based on measurable noise levels from our Chapter 7.5 data, not arbitrary thresholds.

Falsification Hooks: We included specific ablation tests to prove that our new additions (the CF and the Ω channel) were the direct causes of the improved performance.

What the Results Showed
The refined model passed with perfect coherence, proving its robustness at the edges.
100% Pass Rate: The model achieved a perfect pass rate in both the near-zero and anti-aligned regimes, correcting the failures of our previous model.

Clean Decoupling: The antisymmetric channel was confirmed to carry only directional information, as its values were negligible in non-directional cases and flipped sign consistently when the order was reversed.

Why It Matters
This work is the cornerstone of our entire theory.
The valence function is no longer just a hunch; it is now an auditable law with a clear separation of concerns. 
This solid foundation provides the minimal sufficient statistic needed for our objects to propagate consistently into higher-level theories, such as those discussed in our upcoming chapters on geometry and thermodynamics.




