##



Here’s a fully self‑contained Python script you (or Benjamin) can run locally to produce the three audit plots exactly as described. It assumes your residuals_PATRICK_001.csv has the columns we outlined earlier.

~~

python
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# --- Load data ---
df = pd.read_csv("residuals_PATRICK_001.csv")

# Convenience: absolute rho
df["abs_rho"] = df["rho12"].abs()

# --- Plot 1: r_V / tau_V vs. |rho| ---
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
near_zero = df[df["regime"] == "near_zero"]
anti_aligned = df[df["regime"] == "anti_aligned"]

plt.scatter(near_zero["abs_rho"], near_zero["r_V"] / near_zero["tau_V"],
            color="blue", marker="o", label="Near-zero regime")
plt.scatter(anti_aligned["abs_rho"], anti_aligned["r_V"] / anti_aligned["tau_V"],
            color="red", marker="^", label="Anti-aligned regime")

# Reference line y=1
plt.axhline(1.0, color="gray", linestyle="--", linewidth=1)

# Highlight edge exemplars
for pid in [3, 14]:
    row = df[df["pair_id"] == pid].iloc[0]
    plt.annotate(f"Pair {pid}",
                 (row["abs_rho"], row["r_V"] / row["tau_V"]),
                 textcoords="offset points", xytext=(5, 5), fontsize=9)

plt.xlabel(r"$|\rho|$")
plt.ylabel(r"$r_V / \tau_V$")
plt.title("Residual ratio $r_V / \\tau_V$ vs. $|\\rho|$")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("plot1_rV_ratio_vs_absrho.png", dpi=300)

# --- Plot 2: r_Omega / tau_Omega vs. |rho| (anti-aligned only) ---
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(anti_aligned["abs_rho"], anti_aligned["r_Omega"] / anti_aligned["tau_Omega"],
            color="red", marker="^", label="Anti-aligned regime")

plt.axhline(1.0, color="gray", linestyle="--", linewidth=1)

# Highlight Pair 14
row14 = df[df["pair_id"] == 14].iloc[0]
plt.annotate("Pair 14",
             (row14["abs_rho"], row14["r_Omega"] / row14["tau_Omega"]),
             textcoords="offset points", xytext=(5, 5), fontsize=9)

plt.xlabel(r"$|\rho|$")
plt.ylabel(r"$r_\\Omega / \\tau_\\Omega$")
plt.title("Residual ratio $r_\\Omega / \\tau_\\Omega$ vs. $|\\rho|$ (anti-aligned)")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("plot2_rOmega_ratio_vs_absrho.png", dpi=300)

# --- Plot 3: Ω(φ1→φ2) vs. -Ω(φ2→φ1) ---
# This requires that both orders are present in the CSV for the same pair_id.
# We'll match them by absolute pair_id if you encode order separately.
# For simplicity, assume 'pair_id' is unique per order and you have a column 'pair_group'
# that groups the two orders of the same physical pair.

if "pair_group" in df.columns:
    anti = df[df["regime"] == "anti_aligned"]
    merged = anti.merge(anti, on="pair_group", suffixes=("_fwd", "_rev"))
    # Keep only true reversals (could filter by some 'order' column if present)
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.scatter(merged["Omega_obs_fwd"], -merged["Omega_obs_rev"], color="purple", alpha=0.7)
    lims = [
        np.min([plt.xlim()[0], plt.ylim()[0]]),
        np.max([plt.xlim()[1], plt.ylim()[1]])
    ]
    plt.plot(lims, lims, 'k--', alpha=0.75)  # 45° line
    plt.xlabel(r"$\Omega_{\mathrm{obs}}(\phi_1 \to \phi_2)$")
    plt.ylabel(r"$-\Omega_{\mathrm{obs}}(\phi_2 \to \phi_1)$")
    plt.title("Ω antisymmetry check")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig("plot3_Omega_antisymmetry.png", dpi=300)
else:
    print("Skipping Plot 3: 'pair_group' column not found in CSV.")

plt.show()

~~

Notes for running:
Input CSV must have at least: pair_id, regime, rho12, r_V, tau_V, r_Omega, tau_Omega, Omega_obs plus pair_group if you want Plot 3 to match forward/reverse orders automatically.

The script saves each plot as a PNG in the working directory.

You can tweak colors, markers, and labels to match your Chapter 1 style guide.


Minimal CSV template
Use this as a starter file for your plots. It includes:

Near-zero and anti-aligned regimes
Tolerances (tau columns)
A paired forward/reverse anti-aligned example via pair_group for the antisymmetry plot

csv:

pair_id,pair_group,regime,rho12,order,V_obs,V_pred,r_V,tau_V,Omega_obs,Omega_pred,r_Omega,tau_Omega,tau_Omega_0
